value.value: This is any method to determine the nature, properties, or composition of solid biological waste, that is a solid waste produced by a living organism, after that waste has been removed or defecated from the body.

label.value: metabolic cage feces mass measurement method

value.value: This is a method which utilizes a metabolic cage, a housing unit constructed for the separate collection and measurement of liquid and solid waste, to determine the mass of a sample of feces, the bodily waste discharged through the anus.

label.value: metabolic cage food consumption measurement method

value.value: This is a method which utilizes a metabolic cage, a housing unit constructed for the separate collection of liquid and solid waste, to determine the amount of solid or semi-solid food consumed during a fixed period of time.

This is a method which utilizes a metabolic cage, a housing unit constructed for the separate collection of liquid and solid waste, to determine the amount of liquid consumed during a fixed time period.

The Promethion Metabolic /Behavioral Phenotyping System analyzes rat behaviors in real time with second-by-second data acquisition from all sensors. The system is configurable with devices for ingestive behavior studies and activity including cage movement and wheel running. The analysis is driven with SableHDÂ™ (Sable Systems Int.) high-definition digital technology.

This is a method which combines single cell isolation and RNA-seq, which assesses transcript expression and structure via high-throughput sequencing. Sample RNA is purified, fragmented, reverse transcribed to cDNA with the addition of sequencing primers, sequenced and analyzed.

label.value: open field test with visual assessment of in vivo video recording

value.value: An experimental method in which an animal (for example, a rat) is placed in an open field apparatus and the animal's reactions are recorded. These reactions are then evaluated, appraised or perceived by watching the stored sound- and image-based record of the organism.

label.value: elevated plus maze test with visual assessment of in vivo video recording

value.value: An experimental method in which an animal (for example, a rat) is placed in an open field apparatus and the animal's reactions are recorded. These reactions are then evaluated, appraised or perceived by watching the stored sound- and image-based record of the organism.
Temporal interval that defines mouse life from prenatal stage until late adult stage.
Prenatal stage that starts with fertilization and ends with a fully formed embryo, before undergoing last development during the fetal stage.

definition.value: By embryo we mean in the sense of up to the 2nd week postfertilization (beginning of Theiler stage 23), we treat fetus as a separate stage.

value.value: Embryonic stage defined by a one-cell embryo (fertilised egg) with zona pellucida present.

definition.value: "Starts the mouse development sequence, range from embryonic age 0-0.9 dpc (day post coitum). Assumes that fertilization takes place around midnight during a 7pm to 5am dark cycle. Noon of the day on which the vaginal plug is found the embryos are aged 0.5 d.p.c (days post coitum)." [http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Mouse_Stages#Timed_Pregnancy "adapted from"]

value.value: Embryonic stage consisting of division of cells in the early embryo.

definition.value: The different cells derived from cleavage are called blastomeres and form a compact mass called the morula. Cleavage ends with the formation of the blastula.

value.value: Embryonic cleavage stage defined by a dividing 2-4 cells egg.

definition.value: Embryonic age 1 dpc (day post coitum).

value.value: Embryonic cleavage stage defined by a dividing 4-16 cells egg, early to fully compacted morula.

definition.value: Embryonic age 2 dpc (day post coitum).

value.value: Embryonic stage that is an early stage of embryonic development in animals and is produced by cleavage of a fertilized ovum, with formation of a central fluid-filled cavity called the blastocoel.

definition.value: The blastula follows the morula and precedes the gastrula in the developmental sequence.

value.value: Embryonic blastula stage defined by a dividing 16-40 cells egg, with early evidence of the blastocoelic cavity.

definition.value: Embryonic age 3 dpc (day post coitum).

value.value: Embryonic blastula stage defined by a zona free blastocyst (zona pellucida absent).

definition.value: Embryonic age 4 dpc (day post coitum).

value.value: Embryonic blastula stage during which the blastocyst attaches, with first evidence of embryonic endoderm cells covering the blastocoelic surface of the inner cell mass.

definition.value: Embryonic age 4.5 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage04.

value.value: Embryonic blastula stage defined by implantation and formation of the egg cylinder resulting from the rapid increase in the number of inner cell mass cells.

definition.value: Embryonic age 5 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage05.

value.value: Embryonic blastula stage during which the egg cylinder differentiates into embryonic and extra-embryonic regions, and the pro-amniotic cavity appears.

definition.value: Embryonic age 6 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage05.

value.value: Embryonic stage defined by complex and coordinated series of cellular movements that occurs at the end of cleavage.
Embryonic gastrula stage during which gastrulation starts with first evidence of mesoderm and visible embryonic axis.

definition.value: Embryonic age 6.5 dpc (day post coitum).

value.value: Embryonic gastrula stage during which the primitive streak bulges into the pro-amniotic cavity and forms the amniotic fold; the exocoelom appears; the allantoic bud first appears, gastrulation continues and the node becomes visible.

definition.value: Embryonic age 7 dpc (day post coitum), (range 6.5-7.5 dpc). Refers to human CarnegieStage08.

value.value: Embryonic stage called presomite stage and defined by the formation of the neural plate.

definition.value: This stage starts the emergence of the central nervous system at embryonic age 7.5 dpc (day post coitum).

value.value: Embryonic stage at which the ectoderm, endoderm, and mesoderm develop into the internal organs of the organism.
Organogenesis stage during which first somites become visible.

definition.value: Embryonic age 8 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage09.

value.value: Organogenesis stage defined by the turning of the embryo; initiated in embryos with 6-8 pairs of somites and usually completed in embryos with 14-16 pairs of somites.

definition.value: Embryonic age 8.5 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage10.

value.value: Organogenesis stage during which the rostral extremity of the neural tube closes in embryos with usually about 15-18 somite pairs. Late in the stage the 3rd branchial arch becomes visible.

definition.value: Embryonic age 9 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage11.

value.value: Organogenesis stage during which the posterior neuropore forms and the condensation of the forelimb bud becomes apparent near the 8th-12th somite pairs.

definition.value: Embryonic age 9.5 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage12.

value.value: Organogenesis stage during which the posterior neuropore closes and the hind limb bud becomes visible at the level of the 23rd-28th somites.

definition.value: Embryonic age 10 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStages 13 to 15.

value.value: Organogenesis stage defined by the deepening of the lens pit and the first appearance of the physiological umbilical hernia.

definition.value: Embryonic age 10.5 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStages 13 to 15.

value.value: Organogenesis stage during which the lens vesicle gradually closes and the nasal pits start to form. The rapid growth of the brain is striking.

definition.value: Embryonic age 11 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStages 13 to 15.

value.value: Organogenesis stage during which the lens vesicle becomes completely closed and detached from the ectoderm, and peripheral margins of the eye become well defined.

definition.value: Embryonic age 11.5 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage16.

value.value: Organogenesis stage during which the handplate develops angles corresponding to the future digits, and tongue and brain vesicles are clearly visible.

definition.value: Embryonic age 12 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage17.

value.value: Organogenesis stage during which the digit widths and locations can be discerned, and the pinna rapidly develops and forms a crest at right angles to the head.

definition.value: Embryonic age 13 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStages 18 and 19.

value.value: Organogenesis stage during which the fingers are clearly visible and the long bones of the limbs are present.

definition.value: Embryonic age 14 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStages 20 to 23.

value.value: Prenatal stage that starts with the fully formed embryo and ends at birth.

definition.value: This stage describes the four Theiler stages that are commonly reported as equivalent to the human fetal period in the literature. They are anyway defined by embryonic days.

value.value: Fetal stage during which the toes separate and hair follicles are present in the cephalic region but not at the periphery of the vibrissae.

definition.value: Embryonic age 15 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to the human fetal period.

value.value: Fetal stage during which the umbilical hernia disappears and there is a corresponding increase in the size of the peritoneal sac.

definition.value: Embryonic age 16 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to the human fetal period.

value.value: Fetal stage during which the thickened skin forms wrinkles and the subcutaneous veins are less visible.

definition.value: Embryonic age 17 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to the human fetal period. Refers to rat Standard Witschi Stage 34 (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Mouse_Stages#Theiler_Stage_25).

value.value: Fetal stage defined by long whiskers and during which the eyes are barely visible through the closed eyelids.

definition.value: TS26 is used for the period from embryonic day 18 up to birth itself. [https://github.com/tfhayamizu]. Refers to rat Standard Witschi Stage 35 (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Mouse_Stages#Theiler_Stage_26).

value.value: Stage that refers to the newborn mouse, aged E19-20, P0. Description of anatomical structures related to this stage corresponds to the first days of the mouse life. Used for postnatal days 0 through 3.

definition.value: TS27 is used for annotation of postnatal days 0 through 3 (P0 to P3). This is a somewhat arbitrary cut-off but seems to best fit the data we have encountered. TS28 is then used from postnatal day 4 onward. [https://github.com/tfhayamizu]

value.value: Mouse life cycle that starts with fertilization and ends with birth.
Mouse developmental stage that covers the period from birth until 5 weeks old.

definition.value: It is commonly accepted that mouse reaches sexual maturity by six weeks of age (see http://www.ahc.umn.edu/rar/breeding.html).

value.value: Early adult stage that refers to a mouse which is over 2 and under 3 months old.
Early adult stage that refers to a mouse which is over 3 and under 4 months old.
Early adult stage that refers to a mouse which is over 4 and under 5 months old.
Mouse stage that refers to a mouse which is over 5 and under 6 months old.
Mouse stage that refers to a mouse which is over 6 and under 7 months old.
Mouse stage that refers to a mouse which is over 7 and under 8 months old.
